        "journal": "Engineering Structures",
        "abstract": "Fast and reliable prediction of hydroelastic responses is essential for the design and monitoring of flexible offshore structures, yet conventional simulation tools struggle to capture nonlinear and stochastic wave effects efficiently. This study develops a data-driven surrogate based on long short-term memory (LSTM) networks to predict hydroelastic responses of a top-fixed flexible cylinder in irregular seas. Using two sea states with similar spectral characteristics but different nonlinearity levels, we conduct a systematic, experimentally validated assessment of model generalization through within-sea-state validation and cross-sea-state transfer assessment. Results show that while the surrogate performs accurately within its training sea state, its ability to generalize depends strongly on the nonlinear characteristics of the training data. A model trained on the more nonlinear sea state transfers effectively to the milder one, whereas the reverse leads to significant underprediction of peak responses. The findings demonstrate the importance of nonlinear exposure in training datasets and provide practical insight for constructing robust, fast surrogate models for hydroelastic prediction in offshore engineering applications.",
